<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-29T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-29T12:00:00-05:00" n="1129" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1129">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/2382</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                            <gloss type="to">
                                <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                            </gloss>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-29T18:00:00+01:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 29, 1915, 6 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 30, 2.45 p.
                                m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2511. An advertisement of high-explosive shells containing acids, said to
                            have been inserted in <hi rend="italic">American Machinist</hi> for May
                            6 last by Cleveland Automatic Machine Company of Cleveland, Ohio, has
                            been widely reprinted in Germany and is causing unfortunate impression
                            here particularly words “fragments become coated with these acids in
                            exploding and wounds caused by them mean death in terrible agony within
                            four hours if not attended to immediately.”</p>
                        <p>I should be glad to learn status of <hi rend="italic">American
                                Machinist</hi> and whether advertisement is authentic. It seems
                            possible that this is the work of German propagandists in the United
                            States and if so, prompt exposure would be helpful here.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>